Note we already have a convention to detect "category index documents", see 

```js
// By convention, Docusaurus considers some docs are "indexes":
// - index.md
// - readme.md
// - <folder>/<folder>.md
//
// This function is the default implementation of this convention
//
// Those index docs produce a different behavior
// - Slugs do not end with a weird "/index" suffix
// - Auto-generated sidebar categories link to them as intro
export const isCategoryIndex: CategoryIndexMatcher = ({
  fileName,
  directories,
}): boolean => {
  const eligibleDocIndexNames = [
    'index',
    'readme',
    directories[0]?.toLowerCase(),
  ];
  return eligibleDocIndexNames.includes(fileName.toLowerCase());
};
```

It makes sense to find a way to reuse the same logic instead of duplicating it.

We also want to cover such subtle behaviors with unit tests

Also note that with autogeneated sidebars, folders might have a number prefix for ordering reasons, and you may want to strip that number in the infered title: `/xx/yy/03-zz/index.md` should infer to `zz` and not `03-zz`? (see impl of `getSlug()` for inspiration)

Unfortunately, PnP tests failed‚Äîbecause the MDX files will get compiled to JSX files containing something like

```js
/* @jsxRuntime classic */
/* @jsx mdx */
/* @jsxFrag React.Fragment */

import React from "react";
import { mdx } from "@mdx-js/react";

const layoutProps = {
  
};
const MDXLayout = "wrapper"
export default function MDXContent({
  components,
  ...props
}) {
  return <MDXLayout {...layoutProps} {...props} components={components} mdxType="MDXLayout">
    <h1>{`Hello`}</h1>
    </MDXLayout>;
}

;
MDXContent.isMDXComponent = true;
```

Because of the `/* @jsx mdx */` pragma, `@mdx-js/react` is in fact implicitly depended on by the user's site. Theoretically, we could import from the absolute path of `@mdx-js/react` with something like

```js
const code = `
${pragma}
import React from 'react';
import { mdx } from `${require.resolve("@mdx-js/react")}`;

${exportsCode}
${result}
`;
```

But AFAICT, that's discouraged because you should not have absolute paths in loaders' compiled output, which is bad for persistent caching in Webpack.

If you'd like to figure out a better approach in this PR, feel free to... I want to get rid of this as well, so users don't get constantly confused before we migrate to MDX v2.

